{
    "level": "B1",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to build <strong>indirect questions</strong>: first comes a polite frame, and then you use <strong>normal statement word order</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "POLITE FRAME",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "We often begin with phrases such as <strong>Could you tell me... / Do you know... / I was wondering...</strong>:",
            "example": "Could you tell me where the station is?"
        },
        {
            "label": "NO INVERSION",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "After that frame, do not put the verb before the subject.",
            "example": "where the station is, not where is the station"
        },
        {
            "label": "PUNCTUATION",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "If the whole sentence is a polite question, use <strong>?</strong>; if it is a statement containing a question, use <strong>.</strong>",
            "example": "Could you tell me where she is? / I wonder where she is."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Typical patterns",
    "intro": "Indirect questions often overlap with embedded questions, but here the key idea is the polite frame of the whole sentence.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Direct → indirect",
            "title": "Where is he? → Could you tell me where he is?",
            "subtitle": "frame + normal order"
        },
        {
            "label": "Yes / No",
            "title": "Is the shop open? → Do you know if the shop is open?",
            "subtitle": "if / whether for yes/no"
        },
        {
            "label": "Statement with a question inside",
            "title": "I wonder why they are late.",
            "subtitle": "not a direct question in form"
        },
        {
            "label": "Key difference",
            "title": "focus on polite framing",
            "subtitle": "indirect question is about the tone of the whole sentence"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How indirect questions work",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Polite requests",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "Indirect questions are useful when you want to sound <strong>softer</strong> with strangers or in formal situations.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Could you tell me how much this costs?",
                    "ua": "Could you tell me how much this costs?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "Do you know where the manager is?",
                    "ua": "Do you know where the manager is?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "Can you explain why the page is not loading?",
                    "ua": "Can you explain why the page is not loading?"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "A question inside a statement",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "Sometimes an indirect question is part of a statement rather than a separate question.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I wonder where they are now.",
                    "ua": "I wonder where they are now."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I would like to know whether the seats are free.",
                    "ua": "I would like to know whether the seats are free."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She asked me what time the meeting started.",
                    "ua": "She asked me what time the meeting started."
                }
            ],
            "note": "In this case, a full stop is often more natural than a question mark."
        },
        {
            "label": "Similarity and difference from embedded questions",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "Both types use the same word order. <strong>Embedded question</strong> describes the structure, while <strong>indirect question</strong> highlights the function and tone.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Can you tell me where she lives?",
                    "ua": "This has both embedded structure and indirect framing."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I wonder why he left.",
                    "ua": "This is an indirect question without a direct-question form."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Do you know if the bank is open?",
                    "ua": "The frame makes the question less direct."
                }
            ],
            "note": "In practice, the terms often overlap, but the word-order rule is the same."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Inversion after the polite frame.",
            "wrong": "Could you tell me where is the station?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Could you tell me where the station is?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Leaving out if / whether.",
            "wrong": "Do you know is the shop open?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Do you know if the shop is open?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Wrong punctuation.",
            "wrong": "I wonder where she is?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I wonder where she is.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "Indirect questions help you sound more polite and less direct.",
        "After the frame, use normal statement word order.",
        "For yes/no meanings, you often need <strong>if</strong> or <strong>whether</strong>.",
        "Use <strong>?</strong> when the whole sentence is a question; use <strong>.</strong> when it is a statement with a question inside.",
        "The grammar rule is the same as in embedded questions: no inversion after the opener."
    ]
}

